{"schema_version":"1","crate":"gnatcoll_postgres","version":"26.0.0","id":"934c8a04c613cb5c","name":"Header_Pools","qualified_name":"GNATCOLL.Storage_Pools.Headers.Header_Pools","kind":"ada_package","location":{"file":"../../../../home/runner/.local/share/alire/builds/gnatcoll_minimal_26.0.0_cc5dd0a1/d137b4ee70b6031ff2799d79fd7375d2fb07b14760e1adabd5016578ac166b27/minimal/src/gnatcoll-storage_pools-headers.ads","line":109,"column":12},"code":"generic\n   type Extra_Header is private;\n   type Header_Access is access all Extra_Header;\npackage Header_Pools","documentation":{"description":"* For a controlled type:\n\n    1        2                      3\n    +--------+------+-----------------------+\n    | Header | Pad  | Previous+Next+Element |\n    +--------+------+-----------------------+\n    Previous and Next are pointers to other controlled types.\n    In code like:\n            A := new ...;\n    the header pool allocates memory at 1 via malloc, but\n       returns 2 to the compiler\n    then the compiler stores 3 in A.\n    Conversely, when calling Free, the compiler converts A back to\n       2, and our pool converts this back to 1 before calling free()\n    The trouble is that when we call \"Header_Of\" on A, we receive\n    the address 3, so it is harder to find 1.\n\n    See System.Storage_Pools.Subpools.Allocate_Any_Controlled.","formals":[{"name":"Extra_Header","description":""},{"name":"Header_Access","description":""}]},"tagged_types":[{"id":"c8704008870c0335","name":"Header_Pool","qualified_name":"GNATCOLL.Storage_Pools.Headers.Header_Pools.Header_Pool","kind":"ada_tagged_type","location":{"file":"../../../../home/runner/.local/share/alire/builds/gnatcoll_minimal_26.0.0_cc5dd0a1/d137b4ee70b6031ff2799d79fd7375d2fb07b14760e1adabd5016578ac166b27/minimal/src/gnatcoll-storage_pools-headers.ads","line":111,"column":12},"code":"type Header_Pool is new Root_Storage_Pool with null record;","parent_type":{"qualified_name":"System.Storage_Pools.Root_Storage_Poo